{"cursor":"40645","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"{{Infobox scientist\n| name = Vilayanur S. Ramachandran image =\n| Vilayanur_S_Ramachandran_2011_Shankbone.JPG caption = Ramachandran at the 2011\n| Time 100 gala birth_date = 1951 birth_place = Tamil Nadu, India death_date =\n| death_place = residence = San Diego, California nationality = field =\n| Neurology, Psychology work_institution = University of California, San Diego\n| (professor) and Center for Brain and Cognition (director) alma_mater =\n| M.B.B.S. at Stanley Medical College, Chennai; Ph.D. from the University of\n| Cambridge doctoral_advisors = Oliver Braddick, David Whitteridge, FW Campbell,\n| H Barlow known_for = Neurology, visual perception, phantom limbs, synesthesia,\n| autism, body integrity identity disorder prizes = Ariens Kappers Medal from\n| the Royal Netherlands Academy of Sciences; The Padma Bhushan from the\n| President of India; BBC Reith Lectures, 2003; elected to a visiting fellowship\n| at All Souls College, Oxford; co-winner of the 2005 Henry Dale Prize awarded\n| by the Royal Institution of Great Britain. footnotes =\n}}\n\n'Vilayanur Subramanian Ramachandran' (born 1951) is a neuroscientist known for\nhis work in the fields of behavioral neurology and visual psychophysics. He is\nthe Director of the Center for Brain and Cognition, [http://cbc.ucsd.edu/\nCenter for Brain and Cognition\nwebsite] [http://cbc.ucsd.edu/ramabio.html Ramachandran Bio on CBC website] [http://psychology.ucsd.edu/research-\nareas/index.html Psychology Department Webage with link to CBC] and is\ncurrently a Professor in the Department of Psychology [http://psychology.ucsd.edu/people/faculty/faculty-\ngallery.html UCSD Psychology Faculty Directory] and the Neurosciences\nGraduate Program [http://neurograd.ucsd.edu/faculty/detail.php?id=142\nRamachandran Neurosciences Graduate Program Webpage] at the University of\nCalifornia, San Diego.\n\nRamachandran is noted for his use of experimental methods that rely relatively\nlittle on complex technologies such as neuroimaging. Despite the apparent\nsimplicity of his approach, Ramachandran has generated many new ideas about the\nbrain. Anthony, [http://www.guardian.co.uk/theobserver/2011/jan/30/observer-profile-vs-\nramachandran VS Ramachandran: The Marco Polo of neuroscience], The Observer,\nJanuary 29, 2011. He has been called \"The Marco Polo of neuroscience\" by\nRichard Dawkins and \"the modern Paul Broca\" by Eric Kandel. A Brief Tour of\nHuman Consciousness, 2004, Back Cover In 1997 [[Newsweek]] named him a\nmember of \"The Century Club\", one of the \"hundred most prominent people to\nwatch\" in the 21st century. In 2011 [[Time (magazine)|Time]] listed\nhim as one of \"the most influential people in the world\" on the \"Time 100\"\nlist. The citation by Tom Insel, Director of NIH, reads:\n\"Once described as the Marco Polo of neuroscience, V.S. Ramachandran has mapped\nsome of the most mysterious regions of the mind. He has studied visual\nperception and a range of conditions, from synesthesia to autism. V.S.\nRamachandran is changing how our brains think about our minds.\" In\npublic polling of the people included in the 2011 list, Ramachandran ranked 97\nout of 100.[http://www.time.com/time/specials/packages/article/0,28804,2058044_-\n2061021_2061023,00.html] Ramachandran is the author of several books that\nhave garnered widespread public interest. These include Phantoms In the Brain\n(1999) and more recently The Tell-Tale Brain (2010).\n","linknr":807,"url":"Vilayanur_S._Ramachandran","recorded":1375088799,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Vilayanur_S._Ramachandran&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Vilayanur_S._Ramachandran&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang